title: mod for printing of nylon filament using stock xyzprinting firmware no firmware mods neaded

description.text:
xyzprinting filament temperature adjustment to print nylon filament with stock firmware

finally have this dialed in the included picture is a buckle i printed in nylon
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:312961

use ABS cartridge setting

i have finally got a roll of gizmo dork nylon

i have added a 500 ohm resistor parallel to the 500 ohm pot to make the range of the 500 ohm pot to 250 ohms giving a more accurate adjustments
actually the resistor i used is 560 ohms my resistor pack goes from 450 ohms to 560 ohms so not even sure you can buy a 500 ohm resistor so anything close will work

for gizmo dorks nylon set the pot to 190 ohms which is little more than half way on the knob that should be around realy realy scary hot at 290c to 300c this filament requires that high or it will not adhear to lower layers in the amazon comments section it is also mentioned that they where having problems with this filament at normal nylon settings
mid settings on the adjuster should be for normal nylon

then work back and forth till you get the best prints there is still some stringing but not bad enough that it cant be cleaned up i am not sure if this is common with nylon or just this brand of nylon or i nead to do something else like change nozzle dia

i was using the xyzware demo 3dprinter for testing but it seems that this nylon filament is horrabel with realy thin 1 layer vertical walls

so use a demo with thick walls for adjusting the temp

you can use xyzware to get the exact temp by switching the bypass switch in or out
xyzware monitor mode is realy slow to update so you will have to wait till the temp change in xyzware

parts required
1- 500ohm pot
1- 500 ohm resistor
1- single pole single throw toggle switch small radio shack type bypass switch

note i tried to put a knob on the pot but it hit the back of the printer and i believe that it would be better not to have a knob to keep from axadently moving it

this theory will work on any printer that you have no control of the print head temp i am pretty sure that xyzprinting is the only company that is practicing this none sense

description.text:
Design in progress... Things will be changing...

I'm designing a simple coaxial motor mount for a multirotor, using a couple of dirt cheap 2212 motors and other inexpensive components to make a reliable arm that can be used for a Y-6,X-8, or other configurations.

The carbon fiber arm is 10mm OD, and I'm using a 500mm length.

I am also mounting a strip of ws2812b LEDs on the inside of the motor housing, and using a translucent grey ABS for the light to pass through. Test video: https://youtu.be/JUzf5DrLNR4

In this version, the motor mounts are glued to the body. We'll see how later versions go... Some concerns about wall thickness at center. Stress point that could cause layer separation. LED mountings need to be lined up better as well. Completed build test video: https://youtu.be/70FEkei7B7I

Next test will involve propellers...

I'll continue to update as I print and test. Suggestions are appreciated!

description.text: This is a Dremel mount for the cupcake inspired by MarcusWolschon's PCB Mount However, his was for his quick disconnect and the Thingomatic so I made my own. :) http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9280

UPDATE 5/13/12
UPDATE 9/10/12
I started removing two of the three bolts that the wooden platform has holes cut out for and using longer bolts and washers to hold the wooden platform plate securely to the xy carriage. This reduced a lot of x y slop that resulted from the platform moving while only being held by the magnets. You will need:
1 - 100mm x 100mm wooden build platform
2 - 1/4" dia x 100mm shafts
2 - 1/4" dia sleve bearings (XY Linear Bearing)
6 - 8mm nuts (5/16" nuts work)
5 - Little Gold Magnets
1 - 8mm x 120mm all thread (5/16" x 5" all-thread)
4 - 3mm nuts
4 - 3mm x 20mm socket head cap screws
3 - 5mm nuts
3 - 5mm x 20mm socket head cap screws Items with * are in the Makerbot Grab Bag #2 with a bunch of other stuff.
http://store.makerbot.com/grab-bag2.html
http://store.makerbot.com/3mm-gold-magnet.html Steps 1) Print one of each part. 2) Glue the little magnets into the build platform (or use an old unused one without the bright orange acrylic plate) 3) Insert sleeve bearings into both ends of the pusher and a nut into the center. 4) Install Wall 1 to Makerbot wooden platform using the 3mm screws, and nuts 5) Insert the 1/4" x 100mm shafts into each side of the wall. 6) Slide the pusher onto the 1/4" shafts 7) Slide the opposite wall onto the shafts and the other side of the makerbot platform until the 3mm screws can be inserted through the platform and install nuts. 8) Insert Bearings into the bearing holes at the center of each wall. (note they can easily fall out at this point) 9) Insert the 120mm all thread through the bearings and thread into the pusher. Ensure there is an additional bearing on both sides of each bearing. 10) Place an additional nut onto one end of the all thread aligning the hexagons and cut off any additional all thread. 11) Press fit the 8mm Knob onto the two nuts at the end of the all thread. 12) Place the work platform in place of the existing HBP/ABP in Cupcake. 13) Place 3 5mm nuts into holes in the dremel mount. 14) Mount Dremel in place of existing Hot End in Cupcake 15) I created a new machine profile in the Machines.xml specifically for this application. I removed everything in the tools section. (see attached file, Note I that my Cupcake has Gen4 electronics, the Gen3 stopped working) Computer Set-up Within the Skeinforge xx section of the Replicator G (...replicatorg-00xx\skein_engines\skeinforge-xx\skeinforge_application\prefs) I copied the exisiting folder that I used for printing and renamed the file. You will need to modify the "start" and "end" files to remove the temperature references and any moving that might cause interference. Without any real setup in the start.gcode. I have to change the line "G92 X0 Y0 Z0 (set origin to current position)" to "G92 X0 Y0 Zxx (set origin to current position)" where the xx is a layer higher than the first layer in the gcode I just created. I then can set the dremel cutting tool at the top of the part that I am cutting. (if anyone knows a better way to do this please tell me. The first time you print you will need to change the settings from Extrusion to Mill. (Ensure your part is taller than the Layer height or it won't create code and won't tell you why.) Important Skeinforge settings Chop/Layer thickness = height of layers Chop/Perimeter Width (mm) = Tool Diameter Feed/Feed Rate(mm/s)= speed of head while cutting (I slowed mine to 2mm/s to reduce backlash and wear and tear on the bot, it is pretty slow) Feed/Travel Feed Rate(mm/s)= speed of head while not cutting Lift/Clearance above top = height of tool for travel above top layer of cutting Mill/Loop Inner Outset over Perimeter width (ratio) = the amount of material to remove beyond inside perimeter Mill/Loop Outer Outset over Perimeter width (ratio) = the amount of material to remove beyond outside perimeter Drilling Holes Update 9/10/12 I have had issues drilling holes into a part even with the hole diameter 2x the size of the tool diameter. It seems that there is a flaw in the slicing in skeinforge that will not allow the hole to be created. As a workaround. I either use a small drill tool or create a rectangle with one dimension slightly larger than the tool diameter and the other dimension about 2x the tool diameter. Unfortunately it then is a slot. usefull at times but not always what you desire.

Here's a custom design spool holder to hang the filament off the top of the Tevo Black Widow frame without adding much more overall height to the printer.

There's a couple of different designs as pictured. I've personally only printed the plain frame and the tall spindle ends. I made the adjustments to the file afterwards.

The tubing used is pvc pipe with an outer diameter of 21.5mm cut to length. The spindle ends are a VERY tight fit and won't come out again once fitted.

Hanging the spindle off the top rear of the frame like I have done in the pictures will add a lot of extra pulling weight to the frame so make sure it's nice and secure or you may get some movement in your prints.

The spool holder is a very tight fit, but it does fit. Just hook the small kick part in underneath first and then lower the frame over the back.

I had 2 requirements:

  1. The filament had to be positioned over the printer without adding lots of extra height to an already pretty tall printer.
  2. The holder had to be able to be attached securely without to the use of T-Nuts or fasteners. (because I'm lazy and didn't want to go to the hardware store, haha)

From there I measured out the 2080 profile and went to town in Autodesk Maya.

After printing a thinner test print without the crossframe I found the design to already be pretty strong. It flexed a lot but held over 1kg on it's own.

After printing the full design with the cross frames the thing does not move at all.

Bugz are fun little things that are probably the smallest biting 3D print available... the mouth is springy, opens and closes... and they have teeth. Printed with PLA and at least 25% infill should result in a surprisingly strong bite for such a small creature.

comments.text:
Hi.
I made this thing, and it works great!
Biggest issue I had was the huge amount of time I had to spend on post processing the part to remove the gigantic amount of support material it printed with. Maybe this thing would print perfectly fine with no support structure?
I do know my settings were on only 20% infill honeycomb and it is as solid and stable as it needs to be with a 2.2 lb spool on it.

VORON CoreXY 3D Printer (10mm Variant)

Updated STLs to use 10mm shafts and LM10LUU bearings (and some IGUS bearing alternatives)

NOTE: I will be adding more files as I work through my designs and confirm and do final tweaks, starting with Z axis.

Z Axis

  • Upper Support x 4
  • Lower Support x 4
  • Bed Support Carriage A x 2
  • Bed Support Carriage B x 2

Print the included Z Axis parts as well as the standard center bed support coupler and standard stepper mount.

These parts will be a drop in replacement using 10mm shaft and LM10LUU long bearings (you could also use short but long will prevent racking)

XY Axis

  • Left Bracket x 2
  • Right Bracket x 2
  • Main Body x 2

The XY is a completely upgraded joint and has been upgraded to fit the LM10LUU long bearing and 10mm X shafts.

NOTE: There is now an alternative pair of Y-axis brackets that supports the 12mm OD and 10mm ID IGUS bearings, not yet tested, currently printing. These are the same bearings as used on the Tech2C HyperCube

Y Axis

  • A Stepper Mount x 1
  • B Stepper Mount x 1
  • Idler Bottom Bracket A x 1
  • Idler Bottom Bracket B x 1
  • Idler Bottom Rod Holder x 2

Use the standard Idler top mount from the VORON files

X Axis

Recommend using the standard VORON X carriage, run 1012 IGUS bearings and print an adapter to insert them into to fit the LM8UU bearing size on the carriage. This will keep it compatible with future and V1.5 updates.

title: 1.75mm Inline Filament Roller IR Sensor Version 3
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A Kickstarter campaign for this product is live:
https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/522476987/filament-roller
Make a donation and receive a finished Filament Roller. Thanks for your support~

This is a prototype IR sensor and alarm which detects the direction and speed of your 1.75mm filament spool. This sensor will sound an alarm when your spool stops due to:

  • filament-jamming,
  • nozzle-clogging,
  • extruder-grinding,
  • motor-stalling,
  • out-of-filament,
  • or end-of-print.
    If your filament stops moving forward, this sensor will detect it and alert you.

This third version is a compact model designed to fit inline with your filament, close to your extruder. This design is for 1.75mm.

Required parts:

  • 608 ball bearings (2 ea)
  • M3 x 12mm screws (4 ea)
  • M3 x 18mm screws (2 ea)
  • M3 nuts (6 ea)
  • Filament Roller control board (1 ea)
  • Small rubber bands (1 ea)

Printer:

no name i3 clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

This device is fairly easy to print.

The Roller

After printing the roller, you should paint it so it can block IR light.

After the paint dries, then insert the bearing and slip on the rubber band.

A painted roller Assembly

1) Insert a bearing cap and screw the roller into the pylon using an M3x12mm screw.
2) Insert a bearing cap and screw the counter-bearing together using an M3x12mm screw.
3) Screw the pylon to the PCB and case using M3x12mm screws.
4) Screw the counter-bearing assembly to the pylon using M3x18mm screws.

12V Wall Adapters

For powering the board, you can use a 5-24V DC wall adapter. The DC jack should have a 5.5mm outer diameter and a 2.0 or 2.1mm inner diameter.

Alternative Power

Alternatively, you can power the board through directly connecting it to your 3D printer's SMPS.

Do not simultaneously connect a wall adapter and SMPS power to the board at the same time. To do so is hazardous and can permanently damage your equipment.

How to Use

To control the alarm delay, adjust the control knob on the PCB. In the example shown below, the delay is set to 21 seconds and the forward direction of the roller is set to counter-clockwise (anti-clockwise).

Questions

If you have any questions, feel free to post in the comments.

description.text:
My family eats a lot of peanut butter. We buy it in the all natural form so when you get it, there's a puddle of oil at the top and the bottom is hard-packed clay... Mixing the peanut butter is a chore that none of us wants anything to do with.. So I designed this tumbler. Run it overnight with room-temperature peanut butter that is still sealed and the next morning, it will be completely mixed. Sometimes we have to run it a little longer.

You need to print 2 end plates and 4 pipe ends.

The pipe ends have long shafts on them but only one of them needs the long shaft to go into the Rotisserie motor. So when you print the remaining three pipe ends, you can abort the print early or just cut them off.

In addition to the items that you print, you will need to also procure:

4 bearings: https://www.amazon.ca/uxcell®-Skateboard-Groove-Bearings-26x9x8mm/dp/B014R1ST7S

(I know the item description says "Skateboard" but they're not the 608z bearings you're thinking of. These are larger 629ZZ)

1 Rotisserie motor: https://www.amazon.ca/Onlyfire-Universal-Electric-Replacement-Rotisserie/dp/B00X7RKCC4

2 lengths of 1.5" ID black ABS tubing.

1/4" all-thread and nuts.

Some O-rings or rubber bands.

I printed this in both ABS or PLA. I used hair-spray for adhesion and a heated enclosure definitely helps. You will probably need to file the chamfers on the pipe ends to fit snugly into the bearings but I was after a tight fit so it would have enough grab inside the rotisserie motor.

It's not pretty, but it works awesome. I've included the FreeCAD files in case you need to modify anything.

This is my first real project. Suggestions welcome.

description.text:
One of the things I've admired about the Ozo 123 Puzzle bear, apart from the genius of it all, is the connector pin.
It's simple, it works, and best of all, it's easy to print (compared to for example the lego technic/mindstorms connector).

So I've tried to extract the necessary holing to be able to use the pin in other designs.

I have done a few tests and it looks fine, but there should be a way to make it a bit shorter - in that case I'll update it. Or maybe someone else has a good idea?

Before someone accuses me of trying to pad my list of things - I agree this isn't a great invention, since I basically copied what someone else did and measured a few cylinders around it.
But it's a useful tool I think, and since it's not in the original design, I thought why not make it public. Maybe someone can use it. I know I do.

Tinkercad link

https://tinkercad.com/things/9CO0n6pPnYQ

It's public, so you can make a copy and use it in your own designs.

How to use, and what for.

Obviously it's a connector.
The dumbbell part isn't meant to be printed - it's used to cut something away, to make the hole for the pin.

You may need the dumbbell twice, once for each half you want to connect (or not, depending on program).
Make sure that the smaller, inner, section is actually at the edge of the object, it should create a "lip" - this is what will keep the pin secured.

description.text:
I highly recommend to refer to the NEW DESIGN which works a lot better
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2263781

  • If you are making this thing and are happy with it I kindly ask to give it a shout!

==================================================================
Update 2017 Feb. 4th
Old files removed.
Final versiones uploaded.

Modificationes:

  • substantial noise reduction by changes around the fans and inlets
    (less fan-stall/resonance, works like a charm now)
  • support brackets to prevent bending
  • extended duct (to the rear) added.

One certainly would have to rework the section for the clip depending on print-quality.

There is also a small lid for the cables at the front included.
It is not really neccessary, one might use it as one sees fit.
Use styrofoam-glue too to fix it at its place...

Already printed parts are 100% comptible to the new ones.

Take care to fix the fans not too tight to the lower part, especially not the edge.
It is just microns between smooth running and howling...

One more experience to be shared!

  • Keep your hotends well isolated.
    It took me days to find out why my "Marvins" melted away. I 1st thought it to be the duct.
    It turned out that removing the isolation was the reason...

==================
First I want to say that I designed this thing with the greatest respect and gratefulness for http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:537918 which made many a good print possible in the first place.

And still I thought I needed some more cooling power which lead to http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1886734
This one proofed me beeing on the right way, and I gave the 3D-Marvins http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:215703 a try.
But those little fuc..rs would not come out as I wanted them to.
Although this weird little ship http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:763622 got way better
than before I was not entirely satisfied.

My latest duct uses two radial fans and proofed to be worth the effort.
The whole idea is about maximum cooling power with as less weight as possible and the weight as near to the carriage for less vibration.
It sits well on the carriage and powerfully cools under both the nozzels.
At the rear end it may come in contact with the heat-cartridges but it turned out that they make just a small imprint without affecting the function at all. (spacers added Dec. 3rd.)

What you need is, some M3 screws and nuts and two fans like the ones in the picture.
Of the fans I think they are quite common ones. And you can get them for just a few bucks. To cover all needs I attached even the FreeCad files for those who
want to use other ones and need to adjust some dimensiones.
Disassembling mine got a bit hairy (1st one destroyed). It turned out I had to cut the fans base exactly outside of the sticker using a sharp knife. I actually lost some hydraulics...
I recommend to use styrofoam glue to attach them for this glue does not solve PLA and altough it is quite strong it even can be disassembled.

At the bracket one might have to rework at the chamfered edges but it is intended to sit somewhat tight, one would even have to press a little bit on top to get the screw in.

Warning!
The opposing rotary-direction of the fans brings lot of airflow but causes some kind of audible resonance. In other words... This thing whines like a fighter jet at start-run!

proofed to be no problem. There is enough space in the duct.

description.text:
This small lantern is made by using the shade as a mould for the base.

The mould is 3D printed and then the base is cast inside it using fine concrete. When the concrete is dry the design of the mould allows the base to be popped out and separated from the shade.

The properties of the plastic give a great quality of light that shows off the layers from the 3D printing process. The heavy concrete acts as a beautiful and tactile base to the lantern and can be used without the shade if preferred.

The lantern comes from a process that I developed in my architecture degree at the Welsh School of Architecture (Cardiff University). The concept of the design was that it creates a different kind of relationship with physical things. By creating a printable file that had the information within it to become a lantern through a making process that is familiar to most, in this case casting in a mould, anyone could use the file and cast their own lantern relatively easily.

Note: DO NOT try to use a real flame inside the lantern as the plastic will melt! for LED lights that fit you can buy them here:
http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/12x-Waterproof-Submersible-LED-Tea-Lights-Electronic-Candle-Battery-Wedding-Vase-/171891979575

If you'd like to buy a finished lantern you can get them from my Etsy shop here:
https://www.etsy.com/uk/shop/ForgeFive

Notes:

I use 1.6mm wall thickness and 1.2mm top/bottom thickness to strengthen the piece that needs to break off.

Once the piece is printed, I coat the inside in petroleum jelly (good old vaseline) and then carefully pour a fine concrete mix inside. A plaster mix can also be used.

When the mix is dry, I turn the piece over and use pliers to turn the twist release, sometimes this is stiff so I might do the next step before twisting.

I then hold the pliers, or another blunt instrument, against the twist release and hammer the pliers downwards to pop the concrete out of the mould. Be careful to only hit the twist release and not the outside piece of plastic, that will act as the shade.

A bit of sanding and cleaning up and the lantern is good to go.

description.text:
For PLA cooling on the XYZPrinting Da Vinci Full-size (AiO, 2.0, 1.0, 1.0 PRO).
Works GREAT for PLA and with UHU+Glass, doesn't need a heated bed!

Previously, I stated that it's good for ABS fume exhaust, but it moves too much air, therefore creates an unneeded draft that you DON'T want for ABS!

Big 140mm (14cm) fans provide lots of airflow at low dB volume.

  1. Print out a pair (HT140Duct.stl). Z-Rotated slightly, they WILL fit on the build plate of a 1.0 Pro. Not sure about the others. Please comment on your model.
  2. Attach to the side holes of a Da Vinci 1.0/2.0, large format printer.
  3. Use two self-tapping screws per side (drill holes first; see photos) to secure the unit to the printer. The unit will NOT mark or damage your printer, or void your warranty.
  4. Attach a pair of 140mm fans. Some 140mm fans, such as the [noisy] 2500RPM Thermalright TY-143 use the INNER (120mm fan) mounting holes. 120mm fans will also mount up, and you should print out the ADAPTERs for them. (HT120Adapter.stl)
  5. Power two fans EXTERNALLY with a 12V - 1Amp OR HIGHER power supply.
  6. DO NOT power them from the Da Vinci Printer, although a low-voltage relay to switch them on/off might be a good idea... I have yet to set this up on my test model.
  7. Enjoy a whirlwind of PLA cooling from both sides, at the perfect level! You might want open the top lid for better out flow. Jam something into the lid's switch to close the switch.
  8. Please share your MAKE photos!!!
  9. Do not sell/Do not make derivatives!

Here's my recommended FAN (it's loud, though!):
You can see them in the sample video.
http://www.thermalright.com/html/products/fan/ty-143.html

Go with 12V, and avoid 5V USB fans if you want serious results.

The original doesn't fit on my Anet A8. So I remix my own one.

extruder end:
• add hole for extruder motor wire

• remove upper spacer
• reduce elements
• enlarge size deep to reduce collusion from filament and change

change pieces:
• remove upper spacer
• reduce elements
• optimize holes for cable tie (the cable tie replace the upper spacer)
• create a long and a mix size chain piece

z-motor end:
• make is 2cm smaller (otherwise collusion with z-axe may happen end)
• remove upper spacer
• reduce elements
• enlarge size deep to reduce collusion from filament and change
• !!!wire will get more space in next version!!!

I use 22 of the short ones and one of the mid one. If you use the long one, you can reduce the count of the small pieces.

You can see it live here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5MAc2GZp70M

Please note the 4 different ways to "close" the upper space of the pieces.

  1. totally closed, zip tie needs to destroy if you want remove it.
  2. zip tie is fixed, but could open if you want add/remove a line.
  3. zip tie is only jammed and could open/remove so often you want.

description.text:
This is a rather simple remix of mknechts R2D2 remix of InnovationByLayers R2D2.

Much like the scissors in Origami, I consider it to be wrong to use glue with 3D printed parts. Melting (by heat or with ABS, Acetone) is better, but it still lacks finesse.
The best way is to design a model to snap together, or screw together.

Thus I've shaved off a bit at the feet to make more room for the legs, which now have big ungainly holes through which the connector pin (which I took from the 123 Puzzle Bear by emancarrillo) can hold it all together.

The result: a R2D2 you can (to an extend) pose and move his limbs around.
(Be careful, the limbs move very freely.)

I'm sorry about the holes, maybe a nice cover cap would make it better?

The head dome has a sort of plug now, so it should stay on top and can be turned around.
If I were any good at designing, I'd try to get a screw threading in there - that would be ideal, IMO.

The middle leg got a plate that fixes it inside the underside of the torso.

[update 26.12.2016]
I've changed several of the files, tried to add in soft edges where the print often failed, and even shortened the connector pin a bit.
I tried to clean up the dome and body a bit, but that still needs work. As nice as the original model is, it's not easy to print.
The new middle foot now allows more range, it doesn't lock up when you tilt it.

The old files are in the ZIP now, although the new files should fit with the old, it's better to start new.

You may need (the) force to get the pin to connect - I've used strong pliers to force it in. Bothersome, but at least it doesn't stick out as bad as before.
